d Kingdom","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England","Langley, Kent, England":"Langley, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wolston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Woolston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Woolston","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Wol(f)stan</i> (Old English <i>Wulfstān</i>, composed of the elements <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’ + <i>stān</i> stone).","habitational name from Wolston (Warwickshire), Woolstone (Buckinghamshire), or any of various places called Woolston, such as Woolston in West Alvington (Devon), Woolston in Warrington (Lancashire), and Woolston Hall in Chigwell (Essex). The Warwickshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfrīc</i> (genitive <i>Wulfrīces</i>) + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The Buckinghamshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfsige</i> + <i>tūn</i>. The Devon placename probably has the same etymology as the Buckinghamshire placename. The Lancashire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulf</i> (genitive <i>Wulfes</i>) + <i>tūn</i>. The Essex placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wulfhelm</i> (genitive <i>Wulfhelmes</i>) + <i>tūn</i>. There may have been some confusion with   Wollaston  ."]}]},{"name":"Guy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of a compound name starting with <i>witu</i> ‘wood’ or <i>wīt</i> ‘wide’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. In Old French initial <i>w-</i> regularly became <i>gu-</i>. The usual Norman forms of the name were <i>Gy</i> or <i>Guido</i>. In medieval Latin the same name is found as <i>Wido</i>. It was a popular name among the Normans, enhanced no doubt by the romance of Guy of Warwick, recounting the exploits of a folk hero of the Crusades."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":22,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Guy Wolston was born about 1433, in Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England, his father, William Wolston, was 45 and his mother, Margaret Tamworth, was 44. He had at least 3 daughters with Margaret De Huntingdon. He was buried in Buckinghamshire, England."},"et":{"Abt 1433–1490":"umbes 1433–1490","1433–1490":"1433–1490","1433–1503":"1433–1503","1462–1548":"1462–1548","1463–1508":"1463–1508","1466–Female":"1466–Surnud","1390–1480":"1390–1480","1462":"1462","Abt 1433":"umbes 1433","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1390":"1390","1503":"1503","Bef 1480":"enne 1480","1466":"1466","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1487":"1487","Abt 1462":"umbes 1462","1463":"1463","1508":"1508","1548":"1548","Huntingdonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England","England":"England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England":"Huntingdon, Huntingdonshire, England","Langley, Kent, England":"Langley, Kent, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1433–1490":"noin 1433–1490","1433–1490":"1433–1490","1433–1503":"1433–1503","1462–1548":"1462–1548","1463–